<TITLE> Iran president appoints new c.bank governor </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TEHRAN, Sept 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Iran's president has appointed a former economy minister as central bank governor, Mehr news agency said on Tuesday, a change analysts see as a bid by Mahmoud Ahmadinejad to assert more control over economic policy. Outgoing Governor Ebrahim Sheibani's resignation was accepted by the president last month, the third top economic official to leave his post in August. The governor disagreed with the president over interest rate policy, analysts said. The new governor will be Tahmasb Mazaheri, an economy minister in the previous administration and managing director of the Export Development Bank of Iran. His appointment had been widely trailed. A report said last month he had already been appointed. Analysts said the new appointment could herald a more interventionist monetary policy. They saw it as part of an effort by the president to ensure unity in his economic team ahead of the 2008 parliamentary election. "The president has issued the official order to appoint him (Mazaheri) as the new central bank governor. The ceremony to officially introduce him will be held soon," First Vice President Parviz Davoudi was quoted as saying by Mehr. Fars News Agency said the ceremony could take place on Wednesday. Sheibani said earlier on Tuesday that Mazaheri had been chosen but an official order from the president was awaited. Asked why he was leaving, Sheibani told Fars: "I would like to go." The president also changed the oil and industry ministers in August. Both were cabinet members who disagreed with the president over management changes, analysts sa
